Will businesses have to rely more on online collaboration in the future?
text:
In the past decade, there has been a major shift in the way businesses operate. With the advent of the internet and online collaboration tools, businesses have been able to move away from the traditional model of operation. This has resulted in a more distributed workforce, with employees working from home or from remote locations.

The trend looks set to continue, with more and more businesses moving towards online collaboration. There are a number of reasons for this, including the increased flexibility and productivity that it can offer. In addition, online collaboration tools have become increasingly sophisticated, making it easier for businesses to manage and monitor projects.

There are a few things to consider if you're thinking of moving towards online collaboration. Firstly, you need to make sure that your employees are comfortable with the technology. Secondly, you need to have a clear plan for how you're going to manage and monitor the project. And finally, you need to make sure that you have the right tools in place.

If you're thinking of moving towards online collaboration, then it's definitely something to consider. It can offer a number of benefits, but you need to make sure that you're prepared before making the switch.

Ask HN: Applying to YC with a Services Company?
text:
Has anyone been accepted to HN running a services company instead of a product?

I want to apply (again) for Ritza.co - we provide technical publishing as a service. Last time I applied I focused on some SaaS that we were building out in the same space (automatically finding broken links and images in documentation etc), but we have been far more focused on services, so I am thinking of applying directly as a service business this year.

The application form is very focused on product, needing a demo etc, so I'm a bit torn between showing off our WIP SaaS (with no active customers), and rather going into more detail on the services side.

Would love to hear any first hand accounts!
